;; ch11-branching-that-matters.book.slatl
;; Book of Narrative Games — Chapter 11: Branching That Matters

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :chapter-number      11
  :title               "Branching That Matters"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :PG
  :author-lane         "narrative-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + narrative-craft"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"A choice that does not change anything is a lie. Kids catch it faster
than adults. If you offer the player 'kiss her or don't' and the next
scene is identical either way, they will never trust another choice
you offer.

This chapter is the ethics of branching. Every meaningful choice must
alter the game in a way the player LATER encounters. Not immediately.
Not in a rewarded animation right after. LATER — in a scene the
player has almost forgotten was possible.

The physics of consequence: pressure at the start of the game must
be released or paid for by the end. Chekhov called this the gun on
the mantelpiece. In a narrative game every branch is a gun.

---

## 11.1 The three levels of consequence

**Cosmetic** — the choice affects flavor text but not the shape of
the story. 'You wore the blue coat' vs 'you wore the red coat.' The
next scene mentions it once and nothing else changes. Kids catch
this in one playthrough.

**Local** — the choice affects the next scene or two, then falls off.
'You saved Mira' means Mira thanks you next scene, then the story
proceeds as it would have anyway. Adults still notice this pretty
fast.

**Structural** — the choice permanently changes the world. Mira is
alive in some playthroughs; dead in others. The final battle
happens with different allies present. The player who saved Mira in
chapter 3 has a completely different chapter 15 than the player who
didn't.

Aim for structural. Cosmetic is filler. Local is training wheels.
Structural is what narrative games are for.

---

## 11.2 A worked example: the fox

In scene 2 the player finds an injured fox. Three choices: heal it,
kill it, walk past. Each ripples through the game.

```scheme
;; The fox scene, chapter 2.
(define (fox-scene)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"A fox lies in the reeds. Something is wrong with\")
  (paint-text 20 65 \"its leg. It watches you steadily.\")
  (paint-text 20 130 \"[A] heal it\")
  (paint-text 20 160 \"[B] kill it\")
  (paint-text 20 190 \"[C] walk past\")
  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (cortex/write 'state/fox 'healed) (fox-healed-scene))
        ((b) (cortex/write 'state/fox 'killed) (fox-killed-scene))
        ((c) (cortex/write 'state/fox 'ignored) (fox-ignored-scene))))))
```

Three flag values under `state/fox`. Now the game is going to consult
this flag for the rest of the play.

```scheme
;; Chapter 8: the deep-woods scene.
(define (deep-woods-scene)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (case (cortex/read 'state/fox)
    ((healed)
     (paint-text 20 40 \"The fox from before appears from the trees.\")
     (paint-text 20 70 \"She has grown. Her leg has a bend from where\")
     (paint-text 20 100 \"you set it. She leads you to a path you would\")
     (paint-text 20 130 \"not have found.\")
     (cortex/write 'state/fox-guides #t))
    ((killed)
     (paint-text 20 40 \"Bones in the reeds. You feel a small cold\")
     (paint-text 20 70 \"even though the sun is high.\"))
    ((ignored)
     (paint-text 20 40 \"You cross the reeds. The fox is not there.\")
     (paint-text 20 70 \"Something moves in the underbrush behind you.\")
     (paint-text 20 100 \"You do not turn around.\"))
    (else
     (paint-text 20 40 \"The reeds are quiet.\"))))
```

Six chapters after the fox scene, the woods scene checks the fox
flag. The player who healed the fox has an ally now. The player who
killed the fox feels cold in the sun. The player who ignored the
fox has a wildness at their back.

And then chapter 15, the ending sequence:

```scheme
;; Chapter 15: the final approach.
(define (final-approach)
  (cond
    ((cortex/read 'state/fox-guides)
     (paint-text 20 40 \"You take the fox's path. It saves you six hours.\")
     (paint-text 20 70 \"You arrive rested. You will need it.\"))
    (else
     (paint-text 20 40 \"You take the long way. You are tired when you\")
     (paint-text 20 70 \"arrive. You will feel it in the fight to come.\"))))
```

The fox-healed player fights the villain rested. The fox-killed or
fox-ignored player fights tired. The mechanic backing this could be
as simple as HP: rested = 10 HP, tired = 6 HP. Or a specific ally
present in the final scene: rested = fox at your side, tired = alone.

One choice in chapter 2 changed the shape of chapter 8, chapter 15,
and the final battle. That is structural consequence. That is why
players replay narrative games — to see the other branch.

---

## 11.3 The Chekhov principle

Every important object shown in early scenes should be usable or
referenced by late scenes. If you can't find a use for it, cut it
from the early scene.

Keep a design table:

```
scene 2: fox → healed/killed/ignored (payoff scene 8 + scene 15)
scene 3: letter → given to Mira / kept / burned (payoff scene 12)
scene 5: honey → eaten / given away / left (payoff scene 9 shopkeeper)
scene 7: locked box → opened / left / smashed (payoff scene 14)
```

If any early-scene object has no listed payoff, either invent a
payoff or remove the object. This is where writers spend the most
time — figuring out which small things need to matter later.

Not every object needs a payoff. Setting details are allowed. The
'jar of honey on the counter' in chapter 1 might be pure atmosphere,
never referenced again. But CHOICES — meaningful options the player
picks — should almost always echo forward.

---

## 11.4 Foreshadowing the consequence

The best narrative games telegraph that a choice matters WITHOUT
telling the player which choice is 'right.'

```scheme
;; Scene 2 fox choice, with foreshadowing.
(define (fox-scene-with-weight)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"A fox lies in the reeds. Something is wrong with\")
  (paint-text 20 65 \"its leg. It watches you steadily.\")
  (world/after 90
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 100
        \"You feel this is a small moment that will not stay small.\")))
  (world/after 180
    (lambda ()
      (paint-text 20 170 \"[A] heal it\")
      (paint-text 20 200 \"[B] kill it\")
      (paint-text 20 230 \"[C] walk past\"))))
```

'You feel this is a small moment that will not stay small.' That
sentence tells the player the choice will echo. It does not tell
them which choice is right. It just says: pay attention. This is a
gun on the mantelpiece.

Do not do this for every choice. If every choice comes with 'this
will matter,' the player becomes numb. Use it for two or three key
branches in the game. The others should feel casual — and, if you
have done the design work, they will still echo, but as small
touches rather than headline events.

---

## 11.5 The single-playthrough principle

Most players will only play your game once. Design so that ONE
playthrough feels complete and weighted, not so that N playthroughs
combine into one full experience.

This means:
- No single ending should feel like the 'true' ending.
- Every branch should have its own emotional payoff.
- The player who takes the 'wrong' branch (from the writer's
  perspective) should not be worse off — just have a different game.

If you find yourself thinking 'the good ending is the one where they
save everyone,' you have designed a game with one correct branch.
The other branches are punishment routes. Do not do this. Every
branch should be a legitimate story.

---

## 11.6 The impossible fork

Sometimes the player has to make a choice where BOTH options cost
something they care about.

```scheme
;; Save Mira OR save the village. Not both.
(define (impossible-fork)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"The bridge is on fire. Mira is at the north end;\")
  (paint-text 20 70 \"the village is at the south end. You can reach\")
  (paint-text 20 100 \"one before the bridge falls. Not both.\")
  (paint-text 20 200 \"[A] Mira\")
  (paint-text 20 230 \"[B] the village\")
  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (cortex/write 'state/chose 'mira)
             (cortex/write 'state/village-burned? #t)
             (mira-saved-scene))
        ((b) (cortex/write 'state/chose 'village)
             (cortex/write 'state/mira-dead? #t)
             (village-saved-scene))))))
```

Both choices carry a cost. The player who saves Mira lives with the
village burning. The player who saves the village lives with Mira's
death. Either way the rest of the game is heavy.

Impossible forks work because they respect the player's agency
enough to hurt them with it. This is a hard thing to write. Do it
once in your game, maybe twice. Not every scene.

Never give the impossible-fork player a secret third option. 'What
if the third option is a trick and you save both?' That is a
trick. The player who thought they had to choose feels betrayed by
the game. Impossible forks are impossible.

---

## 11.7 The consequence table (design tool)

Before writing scenes, make a table. Left column: choices. Middle
column: immediate consequence. Right column: downstream scenes it
affects.

```
CHOICE                          IMMEDIATE                DOWNSTREAM
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
heal the fox (ch 2)             fox thanks you           ch 8 fox-guides
                                                          ch 15 rested
                                                          ch 16 fox-at-battle

kill the fox (ch 2)             fox dies                 ch 8 cold-feeling
                                                          ch 15 tired
                                                          ch 16 alone-at-battle

give letter to Mira (ch 3)      Mira reads it            ch 6 Mira warm
                                                          ch 12 Mira acts on info
                                                          ch 15 different plan

burn letter (ch 3)              you feel guilty          ch 6 Mira distant
                                                          ch 12 Mira does not act
                                                          ch 15 original plan

honey scene (ch 5)              you eat/give/leave       ch 9 shopkeeper reacts
                                                          ch 11 bees appear
```

Every row is a story-thread. Design the table BEFORE you write. When
you sit down to write scene 8, you already know what the fox line
should look like — because the table says it. This is why writers
who plan branches this way ship games where every choice matters.

Appendix I is a fuller template for this table. Fill it in for your
own game before you write scene 2.

---

## 11.8 A worked scene: the delayed payoff

In chapter 1 the kid gives water to a stranger on the road. In
chapter 14 that stranger turns out to be a healer who knows her by
face.

```scheme
;; Chapter 1: the road.
(define (road-scene)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"An old woman by the side of the road. Waterskin\")
  (paint-text 20 65 \"in her hand. Empty.\")
  (paint-text 20 130 \"[A] give her water\")
  (paint-text 20 160 \"[B] keep walking\")
  (on-key
    (lambda (k)
      (case k
        ((a) (cortex/write 'state/road-water 'gave) (road-thanked))
        ((b) (cortex/write 'state/road-water 'kept) (road-ignored))))))

(define (road-thanked)
  (paint-text 20 200 \"'Bless you,' she says. You do not think much\")
  (paint-text 20 225 \"of it. You have far to walk.\"))

(define (road-ignored)
  (paint-text 20 200 \"She watches you go. You feel it.\"))
```

Fourteen chapters later:

```scheme
;; Chapter 14: the healer's cottage.
(define (healer-cottage)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"You reach the cottage. An old woman opens the\")
  (paint-text 20 65 \"door. Her waterskin is full.\")
  (world/after 90
    (lambda ()
      (case (cortex/read 'state/road-water)
        ((gave)
         (paint-text 20 100 \"'You,' she says. 'Come in. There is no charge.'\")
         (cortex/write 'state/free-healing #t))
        ((kept)
         (paint-text 20 100 \"'I remember you,' she says. 'The rate is double.'\")
         (cortex/write 'state/expensive-healing #t))
        (else
         (paint-text 20 100 \"'You are new here,' she says. 'Standard rate.'\"))))))
```

The player who gave water thirteen hours of gameplay ago gets free
healing. The player who kept walking pays double. The player who
never met the old woman (took a different route) pays standard.

The payoff is thirteen hours of gameplay later. The player who was
paying attention feels a shiver of recognition. That is the shiver
narrative games are for.

---

## 11.9 Common desktop tasks — remembering a customer's preference

An operator asks a first-time visitor 'do you like coffee or tea?'
Not because it matters to the transaction. Because next time she
comes in, the shopkeeper's voice starts with 'the kettle is on —
tea, right?'

```scheme
(define-card 'coffee-or-tea
  :init
  (lambda ()
    (let ((known (cortex/read 'customer/prefers)))
      (cond
        (known
         ;; Second+ visit.
         (scene/imagine)
         (paint-text 20 40
           (string-append \"The kettle is on. \"
                          (case known
                            ((tea) \"Tea, right?\")
                            ((coffee) \"Coffee for you.\"))
                          \" Take a seat.\")))
        (else
         ;; First visit.
         (scene/imagine)
         (paint-text 20 40 \"Welcome. Coffee or tea?\")
         (paint-text 20 100 \"[A] coffee   [B] tea\")
         (on-key
           (lambda (k)
             (case k
               ((a) (cortex/write 'customer/prefers 'coffee)
                    (paint-text 20 160 \"Coffee it is.\"))
               ((b) (cortex/write 'customer/prefers 'tea)
                    (paint-text 20 160 \"Tea it is.\"))))))))))
```

The choice from visit 1 pays off in visit 2. The customer feels
remembered. She IS remembered — by Cortex, but she does not need to
know the mechanism. She just knows the shopkeeper's voice remembers
her tea order and that is a small kindness that adds up.

This is what shopkeepers with good memories have always done. Now it
is available to any operator with fifteen lines of Scheme.

---

## 11.10 Closing

Branch matters. Chekhov. Impossible forks. Delayed payoff. The
consequence table.

Write these into your design before you write your first scene. It
is the single most important discipline in narrative games. Skip it
and your game will feel like a menu; keep it and your game will
feel like life.

Chapter 12 opens a strange new tool: an AI companion in the story
itself. Not the villain, not an NPC — a companion whose job is to
reflect what the player has done back to them. Handled well, it is
the deepest tool in the book. Handled badly, it ruins the whole
game. Chapter 12 is careful.")
